				ECMAScript and View Transitions.
			</p>
			<p>
				JavaScript was created in 1995 by Brendan Eich of Netscape.
			</p>
			<p>
				To standardize the language Netscape submitted JavaScript to the European Computer Manufacturers Association in 1996.
				This led to the first official release of <a href="https://www.ecma-international.org/wp-content/uploads/ECMA-262_1st_edition_june_1997.pdf">ECMA-262</a> in 1997.
			</p>
			<!-- 
			<p>
				I'm a full Stack Engineer who loves to use Node on the backend, 
				PostgreSQL and Express server for data storage and API server, and
				React for the presentation layer. I like using the latest tools at my disposal, things like:
				<ul>
					<li>NextJS, Tailwind and Vercel</li>
					<li>TypeScript with the latest updates in ECMAScript</li>
					<li>AWS to authenticate users, serve up sites and assets, and handle heavy loads</li>
				</ul>
			</p>
			-->
			<p>
				As a full stack engineer who uses both Node on the backend and React with JavaScript/TypeScript on the frontend these updates are wonderful. 
				The options continue to increase adding better options to write increasingly better code. 
			</p>
			<p>To find out more about: </p>
			<ul>
				<li>ECMAScript versions, take a look at the <code><a href="/astro-transition-typescript/blog">Blog</a></code></li>
				<li>Me, take a look at the <code><a href="/astro-transition-typescript/about">About</a> section</code></li>
				<li>Sources for ECMAScript information, take a look at <code><a href="https://github.com/ibbrett/astro-transition-typescript/tree/master/README/README-REFERENCES.md">References</a> readme</code></li>
			</ul>
			<p>Enjoy!</p>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>
